description: Prime Minister François Bayrou's impending downfall stems from his inability to win over the Socialists. They now face a difficult choice between finding an agreement with Macron's coalition or maintaining a stance of radical opposition, observes Le Monde columnist Françoise Fressoz.

headline: Chikungunya: Ixciq, the first authorized vaccine against the virus, under scrutiny
description: The United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has suspended the vaccine developed by Franco-Austrian laboratory Valneva. In France, its use has been restricted to people under 65 after three deaths in La Réunion. As early as the clinical trials, 1.8% of patients reported serious adverse effects.

headline: At the Venice Film Festival, a showcase of men in crisis
description: From 'The Smashing Machine' to 'Frankenstein,' the film competition features a multitude of works centered on male characters grappling with troubled identities.

headline: Arlette Farge, historian: 'Today's isolated and abandoned youth do not know where their future lies'
description: 'May '68 Thinkers Reflect On Trump Era' (3/6). The researcher and feminist expresses concern about the early emergence of violence among some young people, as well as about a system of incarceration that fosters repeat offenses.

Xi and Putin's strategic friendship
description: Russian President Vladimir Putin arrived in Beijing on Tuesday, on the eve of a major military parade, for what was at least his 45th meeting with Chinese President Xi Jinping since both leaders have held power. Their close ties reflect the alliance Russia and China have forged against the West.

headline: For France's teachers, a back-to-school season marked by growing weariness
description: While they still say they love their profession, teachers expressed growing fatigue in the face of overcrowded classrooms, ever-dwindling resources, and nonstop reforms that leave their jobs uncertain. As a result, many are considering leaving the field altogether.

headline: Venice Film Festival: Julia Roberts shines in Luca Guadagnino's 'After the Hunt'
description: The American actress plays a woman torn between ambition and principle in this film, presented out of competition, which examines morality and ethics in the wake of #MeToo.
